description: {"blocks":[{"key":"27e1v","text":"This is part of the collection \"DToL Taxon-specific Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) for the Plant Working Group\". The SOP collection contains guidance on how to process the various land plant taxa within the scope of the Darwin Tree of Life project. The guidance specifically refers to the tissue samples needed for DNA barcoding (which takes place at the Royal Botanic Garden (RBGE)) and outlines the flash frozen tissues required for whole genome sequencing (WGS), which takes place at the Wellcome Sanger Institute . Every specimen is submitted for DNA barcoding first before potentially being sent to the Wellcome Sanger institute.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a95sr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2q49v","text":"This Sample Collection SOP outlines the collection of plant samples for the Darwin Tree of Life project. DToL aims to generate high quality genome sequences from these samples. To achieve this goal the DToL Genome Acquisition Labs (GALs) must access a sufficient quantity of healthy living material, preserve it in a manner that conserves its DNA quality, and supply it to the appointed sequencing facility. Material must also be available and appropriately preserved for DNA barcoding, flow cytometry and herbarium vouchers. In some instances, material for RNA extraction is also required. It is the responsibility of the GALs to also link accurate and information-rich metadata to all collections.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bms09","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9chgj","text":"Definition: Bryophytes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":10}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1oo2g","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7u1nk","text":"Including: Bryophyta, Marchantiophyta, Anthocerotophyta. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"94u6q","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fk984","text":"Excluding: ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4lcoi","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5jfa","text":"Sample collection vessels for genome sequencing","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":47}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e6p8h","text":"Bulk collection into sample containers: We encourage bulk sampling of a clump of bryophyte material in the field, for subsequent processing in the lab at the Genome Acquisition Lab. Sample containers are sealable plastic tubs. Each container should be directly labelled. We recommend the inside bottom of these collection tubs be lined with kitchen roll dampened with water, to prevent the plants drying out, and that the tubs be quickly shipped/returned to the Genome Acquisition Lab in a cool box or on ice packs where possible (or at ambient temperature if that is similar to their natural growth conditions).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cbs2u","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dijcr","text":"Sample collection for DNA barcoding","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":35}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9eoru","text":"Plant DNA barcoding for the Darwin Tree of Life project is carried out at the Royal Botanic Garden, Edinburgh (RBGE). The majority of the sample sorting of bryophyte material for DNA barcoding will be undertaken in the labs at RBGE, not in the field. Thus the default position is collection and transport of fresh plant material in plastic tubs with dampened kitchen roll.  However, individual bags of silica gel desiccant can be provided for the preservation of plant material for DNA barcoding by other institutes or for use in the field where required. Material that cannot be delivered in-person to RBGE should be sorted into ziplock bags and posted using Royal Mail first class delivery.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"351fr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"45hup","text":"Sample collection for genome size estimation","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":44}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ai3e3","text":"Genome size estimation is carried out at RBG Kew. Plant material should be stored between sheets of damp, cool tissue-paper in a zip-lock bag in the field, or retained in the tubs with the bulk material and sorted into a zip-lock bag at the Genome Acquisition Lab. Material should be stored in a refrigerator at 4°C prior to being posted to RBG Kew. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dl0lc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"b0qah","text":"Herbarium voucher collection","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":28}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"86jg9","text":"For the vast majority of bryophytes samples, voucher material will be processed at the Genome Acquisition Lab at RBGE, from the bulk material collected.  If appropriate, however, the collection of voucher material can be made at the time of genome sampling in the field by separating some of the collection into a labelled envelope or folded paper packet, and leaving it to air dry. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"832ap","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":2,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"8a3pd","text":"Metadata ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5h9qt","text":"Please refer to the online version of the Recording Sample Metadata for DToL SOP for up-to-date information and instructions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9sqlt","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":3,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"8v4k9","text":"Photographs","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6bc4m","text":"","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"320n9","text":"Habitat photos. Please save as JPG for upload to BOLD. Images should be named in a standard manner, preferably by the collector number as it appears in the manifest, a one-word description, and a number if there are several images in a series, e.g. MR204_habitat_1.jpg, MR204_habitat_2.jpg.","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":16}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4l896","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4snu9","text":"Plant habit photos. Please save as JPG for upload to BOLD. Images should be named in a standard manner, preferably by the collector number as it appears in the manifest, a one-word description, and a number if there are several images in a series, e.g. MR204_thallus_1.jpg, MR204_thallus_2.jpg; MR204_seta.jpg.","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":20}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2vb9n","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6426v","text":"","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4vtv9","text":"","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"engse","text":"Collection of bulk samples in the field","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":39}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9ge0n","text":"It is critical that the sample is healthy living material when it is processed into specimens and placed in the FluidX tubes. We recommend the collection of bulk samples of bryophyte material in the field, followed by processing in a lab, with use of a dissecting microscope for sample cleaning and close-up photography. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"60clv","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ffs3g","text":"If the species is known to be dioicous and sexual organs are present in the field, where possible a note should be taken of whether the specimen being sampled is male (with antheridia) or female (with archegonia, or with sporophytes attached). If both sexes are present at a site, they should both be sampled, so that a decision about which is most suitable for genome sequencing can be made after the collections have been genome sized - and allowing for potential additional sequencing or resequencing of the other sex.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dsgbn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9bnl8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"trfn","text":"Procedure","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1kmn9","text":"Line the sample container with H2O dampened kitchen roll. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"97knd","text":"Using a clean trowel or knife if required, sample a clump of bryophyte material, taking (if necessary) only a shallow layer of substrate. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6kj7t","text":"Remove any unconnected plant material and insects. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4l0f3","text":"Place the sample in the assigned sample container, ensuring the lid can fully seal.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ab11l","text":"On occasion, it may be necessary to collect multiple unconnected clumps of material to obtain sufficient material and/or for barcoding/voucher/flow cytometry. Collect any unconnected material into a different labelled sample container.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fr1n2","text":"Place the sample container(s) in the cool box or on the ice packs.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dq0ir","text":"Complete the mandatory fieldwork collections columns in the sample manifest and the data checklist provided.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"42mhr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dhe4e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4ftbk","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9iq9v","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"921b3","text":"Lab-based processing","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":20}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"79aft","text":"Purpose: Correct processing methods of specimens to ensure the delivery of sufficient quantities of high quality preserved plant material for genome sequencing; correct processing methods of specimens for DNA barcoding, flow cytometry and herbarium vouchers; collation of rich metadata describing the specimens and catalogue of images for taxonomic description and public engagement literature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8a2k9","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7liuh","text":"Specimens for genome sequencing","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":31}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dqseq","text":"It is critical that the plant material is healthy and living when it is processed into specimens and placed in the FluidX tubes. Samples must be processed in a clean and preferably cool environment, therefore we recommend processing the samples, using a binocular microscope, in a petri dish that sits on wet ice. Only FluidX barcoded tubes will be accepted at Sanger, either 1.9ml or 7.6ml. To ensure maximum DNA recovery, the specimens must be frozen as quickly as possible in the FluidX tubes, using either a FluidX cooling rack, dry ice or Liquid nitrogen.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eqb52","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":4,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"a6ikl","text":"Quantities of tissue required:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":30}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cmv6a","text":"Genome sequencing: please collect up to 10 tubes per specimen. DO NOT PACK TISSUE TIGHTLY INTO THE TUBE. Sanger requests at least 150mg of plant tissue per 7.6ml FluidX tube (May 2022). This will not be possible for many bryophytes - in these cases, collect as much as possible.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":186,"length":92}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9mht6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d2g86","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":5,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"3ovqc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8ivi7","text":"Procedure","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4r2i6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8inoq","text":"Precool the FluidX cooling rack and/or FluidX tubes on dry ice. We recommend the use of a FluidX cooling rack so that tubes are stable and at the right temperature to receive tissue.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7jgj4","text":"Gently remove any substrate material (soil/plant debris) from a clump of the sample as follows: wash thoroughly with several changes of water, gently rubbing at any clumps of dirt with a mounted needle or no. 5 forceps to loosen it. Blot dry between rinses with tissue paper or filter paper (which can also help remove some of the dirt). Remove rhizomes with either forceps or a scalpel, particularly if they're dense, as they can contain a lot of dirt and fungi. Place all waste material into an autoclave bag for safe disposal.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"47rc7","text":"Place the cleaned material into a 100mm petri dish with a little water. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"37u8i","text":"Working with the petri dish on wet ice, gently tease the clump of tissue apart, taking care to keep connected strands intact.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"77ohu","text":"Using clean tweezers, carefully remove a strand or segment of tissue no wider than 10mm or longer than 70mm (for use of 7.6ml tubes). Place the specimen into a single pre-chilled FluidX tube, noting the barcode number/rack position. Please do not fill tubes to the top as it is then not possible to get the tissue out without risk of thawing. Note: Read manifest SOP on the correct use of ID numbers for multiple specimens from the same individual sample vs bulk sample. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":343,"length":126}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fvtrl","text":"With the FluidX tubes still on dry ice, transfer the samples to the -80oC freezers and register the sample in the DToL Manifest. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d7req","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"tl6i","text":"All tissue must be kept as cold as possible as fast as possible, so whenever possible place the tubes containing specimens immediately into the -80oC freezer for storage until shipping to the Sanger Institute, Dry ice and liquid nitrogen are suitable for material for genome sequencing.  Wet ice and -20oC freezers are not suitable at any point for the storage of FluidX tubes containing these samples, and freeze/thaw cycles must be avoided.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"43r2p","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dffkf","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ftk5f","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":6,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"6pcog","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"22i4l","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"61tkj","text":"Shipping samples to the Sanger Institute.","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":40}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"av9ff","text":"Information taken from the Sanger DToL sample Submission SOP July 2020. Please refer to the online document for up to date information and instructions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6ql21","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"erdfa","text":"Prior to shipping any samples, the sample manifest needs to be completed and sent to treeoflifesamples@sanger.ac.uk whereupon the manifest will be checked and validated. You will be provided with a unique Sanger TOL Sample RT tracking ID for that batch of samples. Once your manifest is approved you will receive back a validated version and the Sanger TOL Samples team will agree with you when to ship your samples. Do not ship any samples until your manifest has been approved. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6fr1t","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2qn4f","text":"","type":"header-four","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8oahp","text":"Samples for DNA barcoding","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":25}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ac5s4","text":"DNA barcoding is used as part of the species identification process AND sample tracking (to check that the genome sequence corresponds to the material that was sent and that there have been no sample mix-ups). It is therefore crucial that wherever possible, the material used for DNA barcoding relates to the same genetic individual sent for genome sequencing. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a367p","text":"However, due to the amount of tissue required for genome sequencing, and the small size of most bryophytes, it will often be necessary to DNA barcode representative material (i.e. proxy barcoding) of the specimen that is genome sequenced, rather than sequencing the same genetic individual.
